results.notes:
On a lawn. I have found what is very likely this species in the same location (4 square yards) occasionally for the past 5 years. As with the older observations, the spores don’t exhibit the pronounced “snout” seen in the photo at Mushroom Expert. However, a few of the spores seen here do show a snout; seems the alignment needs to be just right to see this feature. C du Q says the spores of C. erebia verge on boletoid, which is an apt description for some of the ones seen here. Spore dimensions 11-13 × 5-6 are within the range reported on ME. In some older collections of mine I recorded smaller dimensions, but this may have been due to my not applying a +17% which I have since determined is necessary, or I may have included spores that were not positioned so that the full length is seen.

Lawn habitat differs from ME’s characterization of C. erebia as a woodland species.

DNA confirmed T Dulciolens.
This mushroom grows at the same time of year as Tricholoma Magnivelare and has many similarities. It has a similar but distinctly different smell, always grows from the same blue/gray soil, and emerges from the ground in the way. The smell is a little less dirty sock, and a lot more cinnamon. It’s a very pleasant smell.
The tree association seems to be Spruce exclusively. They are smaller and more slender than T magnivelare, and have a different color, which is slightly both lighter, and more beige. I have eaten these every fall for three years now. They have a good bitter flavor that reminds me of black coffee.
The ID of T Dulciolens was given to my photos last year on a group forum, by a published mycologist. I recently saw a new publication on T Dulciolens in the Sierra Nevadas and British Columbia. The description and pictures don’t seem to match up with what I have here. I will be sending a dried specimen for DNA testing.

results.notes: Very tiny basidiomata fruiting on moss/lichen covered bark of Pyrus calleryana following some intermittent rain, first rain in approximately a month, collection consisting of about 15 specimens; Macro: Pileus up to about 1.5 mm (the largest basidiocarp collected), ovoid to bell-shaped, finely pubescent, becoming more glabrous in age, sulcate (nearly to disc in age), bluish-grey when young, turning brownish to chestnut brown in age/drying; Lamellae distant, mostly adnate with a decurrent tooth, concolorous with pileus, edges slightly paler, lamellulae present; Stipe 2-5 mm long ~0.5 mm thick, finely pubescent, upper concolorous with pileus, lower portion more reddish brown in color; Odor/Taste odor nondistinctive, did not taste; Micro: Basidiospores nearly globose to barely subglobose, smooth with a very small apiculus, hyaline or with granulose-like contents, amyloid, ~ (8.5) 9.1 – 10.0 × 8.0 – 9.2 μm; Basidia mostly 4-spored, some 2-spored scattered with clamps, clavate, 26 – 38 (42) x 7 – 11 μm; Pleurocystidia absent; Cheilocystidia abundant, clavate to inflated-cylindrical, clamps frequent at bases, upper portion covered with rod-like excrescences, of which some branched or slightly curved, ~ 18 – 36 (40) x 7 – 17 μm; Lamellar trama essentially regular, dextinoid in Melzer’s; Pileipellis consisting of densely packed pellicle layer of pileocystidia, forming coralloid masses, irregular, diverticulate or with longer excrescences, underneath consisting of a cutis with smooth to sparsely diverticulate hyphae; Pileocystida abundant, forming a mass of hyphae at uppermost cuticle layer, irregular, sometimes branched, extremely diverticulate, pale brownish to golden, up to about 30 – 35 μm in length; Stipitpellis a cutis, medullary hyphae essentially smooth, 2 – 4 (5) μm thick, hyaline to yellowish to very pale brown, cortex layer with scattered diverticuli or cylindrical excrescences; Caulocystidia irregular, very diverticulate, similar to pileocystidia, though not really branched as often, up to about 35 – 40 μm in length, pale golden-brown; Clamp Connections scattered and inconsistent within hymenium, sometimes at bases of cystida/basidia, scattered in lamellar hyphae, clamp connections pretty common elsewhere.
